\par The historical influence of Persia, now Iran, on the peoples of Afghanistan can be seen by the number of ethnic groups who speak }{\i\fs24 Dari}{\fs24 , the name given to the various dialects of Afghan Persian. The Tajiks are the lar
gest and most influential of these groups, and the second largest ethnic group within Afghanistan following the Pashtun.
\par Believed to be the original Persian population of Afghanistan and Turkmenistan, the Tajiks live in an area stretching from northern Afg
hanistan, across the border from Tajikistan, into the Hindu Kush. They often identify themselves by the particular valley they live in or near. 
\par The Afghan Tajiks are light-skinned Caucasians with aquiline noses and black hair. They share the Caucasian loo
ks of the Iranian peoples, as well as their language. Tajiks constitute an estimated one-quarter of the population of Afghanistan. Half of the Afghans who have fled to Pakistan since 1979 are Tajiks, and approximately 65% of Afghan refugees in the United 
States belong to this group. Both Tajiks and Uzbeks have been displaced from their traditional homes by expanding Pashtun tribes.
